<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Exclusively found in deeper soft sediment habitats outside coral reef habitats, where it exhibits an endo-benthic substrate preference. Depth 14-20 m.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burn" authorityYear="1974" class="Gastropoda" family="Aeolidiidae" genus="Cerberilla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerberilla incola" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="incola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Cerberilla incola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from Australia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00852988.1974.10673877" author="Burn, R" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Malacological Society of Australia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="43 - 57" refId="B35" refString="Burn, R, 1974. Notes on some benthonic opisthobranchs from Port Phillip Bay, Victoria. Journal of the Malacological Society of Australia 3: 43 - 57, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00852988.1974.10673877" title="Notes on some benthonic opisthobranchs from Port Phillip Bay, Victoria." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00852988.1974.10673877" volume="3" year="1974">Burn 1974</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="RÃ©union">Reunion</normalizedToken>
Island (
<bibRefCitation author="Bachel, S" journalOrPublisher="Publications of the Seto Marine Biological Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" refId="B15" refString="Bachel, S, 2010. Cerberilla incola from the Indian Ocean. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" title="Cerberilla incola from the Indian Ocean. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" year="2010">Bachel 2010</bibRefCitation>
). First documented from the Gulf of Thailand by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-012-0141-4" author="Chavanich, S" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="31 - 36" refId="B49" refString="Chavanich, S, Viyakarn, V, Sanpanich, K, Harris, L, 2013. Diversity and occurrence of nudibranchs in Thailand. Marine Biodiversity 43: 31 - 36, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-012-0141-4" title="Diversity and occurrence of nudibranchs in Thailand." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12526-012-0141-4" volume="43" year="2013">Chavanich et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burn" authorityYear="1974" class="Gastropoda" family="Aeolidiidae" genus="Cerberilla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cerberilla incola" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="incola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Cerberilla incola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as described by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00852988.1974.10673877" author="Burn, R" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Malacological Society of Australia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="43 - 57" refId="B35" refString="Burn, R, 1974. Notes on some benthonic opisthobranchs from Port Phillip Bay, Victoria. Journal of the Malacological Society of Australia 3: 43 - 57, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00852988.1974.10673877" title="Notes on some benthonic opisthobranchs from Port Phillip Bay, Victoria." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00852988.1974.10673877" volume="3" year="1974">Burn (1974)</bibRefCitation>
represents a largely brown animal with dark brown rhinophores, dark brown lines across oral tentacles and along lateral and central lines of the dorsum with central cerata tipped with dark arrow-shaped marks. A later observation from near the type locality of South-East Australia (
<bibRefCitation author="Cobb, GC" journalOrPublisher="Planta" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23659" refId="B54" refString="Cobb, GC, 2010. Cerberilla incola from sthn Queensland. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23659" title="Cerberilla incola from sthn Queensland. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23659" year="2010">Cobb 2010</bibRefCitation>
) highlighted a light brown to nearly white specimen with pale blue lines along oral tentacles, a distinctive yellow-orange band along the anterior portion of the head, and with most cerata bearing parallel lines ranging from light to dark brown. A further observation from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="RÃ©union">Reunion</normalizedToken>
Island in the Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation author="Bachel, S" journalOrPublisher="Publications of the Seto Marine Biological Laboratory" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" refId="B15" refString="Bachel, S, 2010. Cerberilla incola from the Indian Ocean. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" title="Cerberilla incola from the Indian Ocean. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" year="2010">Bachel 2010</bibRefCitation>
) was also considered to be 
<taxonomicName genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. incola" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="incola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">C. incola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rudman, WB" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Molluscan Studies" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" refId="B224" refString="Rudman, WB, 2010. Cerberilla incola from the Indian Ocean. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" title="Cerberilla incola from the Indian Ocean. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/23150" year="2010">Rudman (2010)</bibRefCitation>
bearing the same parallel lines along the cerata but lacking in the yellow-orange band of the earlier observation. All animals appear to have dark brown-grey rhinophores and the same dark colour anterior to the pericardium. Specimens from Koh Tao have been observed to show external variability (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. A, B Aeolidiopsis ransoni 23 mm (A) and 25 mm (B) C Baeolidia salaamica 10 mm D Cerberilla ambonensis 20 mm E Cerberilla asamusiensis 8 mm (photograph by Pau Urgell Plaza) F, G Cerberilla cf. incola variants 12 mm (F) and 7 mm (G) H Cerberilla sp. 22 mm I Limenandra confusa 12 mm J Caloria indica 26 mm K Favorinus sp. 1 5 mm L Favorinus sp. 2 5 mm" figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1042.64474.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/553111" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">17F, G</figureCitation>
) and further investigation is required.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
